{
  "text": "Another factor affecting migrants' ability to find work is their often limited social capital [CITATION_1] . Here, marriage migrants may have a comparative advantage over other migrants, as their connection to a local family may provide valuable contacts for employment [CITATION_2] . Studies in the United States, Sweden, and Spain, however, found that family migrants are less likely to be employed than labour migrants, even after accounting for human capital characterictics [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
